<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="JON" stage="Final" version="A">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2014-12-15 03:14:56Z" when="2014-12-15 03:14:56Z" stage="Draft">Consultant Check, 4 Dec 2014 at UBB; Consultant: Catherine Rountree:; questions put by proxy by Chuck Grimes: Consultant Report: Kupang JONAH report-CEG-1.doc &amp; CR queries on Kupang Jonah-compiled.pdf; approved by CR email 11-Dec-14; UNSs: 1: Erni Sine, f. 25; Wiwi Paulus, f. 23, Kristin Dethan, f. 20, Rina Fernandes f. 22 (see report for more details). non-UNSs present: Adriana D-T (UKAW), Reny (UNDANA)</Message>
      <Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2014-12-19 06:55:26Z" when="2014-12-19 06:55:26Z" stage="Rev">smoothing read thru for Kupang mini-Bible at UBB with Chuck, Oma Ora and Rina Fernandes.</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Yunus<bt>Jonah</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Yunus pung Carita<bt>Yunus' Story</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan Allah pange sang Yunus, ma Yunus lari<bt>God calls Yunus, but Yunus runs/flees</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Dolu-dolu, ada satu orang Isra'el, nama Yunus. Dia pung bapa, nama Amitai. Satu kali, TUHAN Allah utus sang Yunus ko kasi tau Dia pung pasán bilang,<bt>Long ago there was an Isra'el person named Yunus. His father was named Amitai. One time the LORD God sent/commissioned Yunus to tell/explain His message/instructions saying, [DISCOURSE: Reordered to set background-foreground.] [NOTE: Historical context of book: Israel and Assyria were enemies at this time--8th century (around 780; 2 Kings 14:25) BC. (CEV Intro, TN Intro, HCE note, AM intro) Allen (1:1) says “In the minds of the listening circle Nineveh stood for the essence of human self-exaltation and anti-God power.” Allen at 1:1 also notes “Yahweh in his mysterious providence had inspired the prophecy and its fulfillment, but the nationalistic sentiments have for Judeans something of the flavor Hitler’s Lebensraum policy has for non-Germans. A shadow of prejudice has been cast over the initial favor with which the story was first received.” And Jonah knows his task would be extremely unpopular with God-fearing Jews. The term “the great city of Niniveh” “connotes what is big and bad, an intolerable affront to God.” So God sends Jonah to preach repentence and show mercy to Israel's enemies. That blind prejudice and hate helps explain why Jonah is so resistant to the idea, and so upset when God responds to their repentance, rather than destroy them, as Jonah would prefer. Among other things, this is very much a story about God confronting a man with his own prejudice, and the inappropriate responses which that blind prejudice triggers. Allen (and others) also points out that the name Jonah means “dove” and is a symbol for Israel.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yhwh: Since in the first"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayhi: consecutive-like, but legitimate</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔel: to, directed to (no"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yonah "dove", Jewish tradition has him as the son of the Zarephath widow</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) dvar: word, matter. rheema is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) dvar: word, matter. rheema is used in a similar way in Luke 3:2 for the start of John da Baptiza Guy's life work.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yonah &quot;dove&quot;, Jewish tradition has"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔel: to, directed to (no verb; a technical term for prophesying, though this book never uses "prophesy". Used around 40 times in Jeremiah, 50 times in Ezekiel)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayhi: consecutive-like, but legitimate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yhwh: Since in the first part of this book thereʔs an antithesis between Jonah's God Yahweh and the gods of the sailors, we use the proper name. Once the sailors are out of the way, we revert to the old Jewish usage "Yahweh" (the # triggers a macro with small caps), though nowadays Jews seem to always say "the Name." Even in Nineveh there's no mention of the gods of Nineveh, only of the sin of Nineveh. Yahweh deals with Jonah as "Yahweh," but the Ninevites speak of him only as "God."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Background: Jonah was a prophet from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">Background: Jonah was a prophet from the town of Gath Hepher in northern Israel (although the word ‘prophet’ and ‘prophecy’ do not occur in this book). He lived in the time of Jeroboam II, a bad king of Israel who did some good things. At that time the Assyrians were enemies of the Israelites. Nineveh was the capital city of Assyria. The Book of Jonah is read in Yom Kippur ritual. Was in the liturgy for Holy Saturday for RC, still is for Orthodox.</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Raja-raja dong 14:25</note><v n="2" />&lt;&lt;Dengar, é! Sakarang lu jalan pi sablá matahari nae di negara Asiria pung kota bésar, andia Niniwe, yang bamusu deng Isra'el.<bt>&lt;&lt;Listen, é! Now you go/travel to the east to the country of Asiria's large/main city, that is Niniwe, who are enemies with Isra'el.</bt><note reference="1:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Orang pintar so'al Alkitab dong bilang, itu waktu Isra'el bamusu deng Asiria, andia ko Yunus binci mati sang dong. Jang sampe ada dia pung kelu ko, orang yang dia kanál yang su jadi korban. Apalai orang Niniwe dong sonde kanál sang Tuhan Allah. Jadi Tuhan minta Yunus pi layani orang yang dia binci deng lia deng mata sablá sang dong, ma Yunus simpan hati talalu. Niniwe tu, jadi kota bésar di negara Asiria. Ada 120.000 orang yang tenga di kota Niniwe. Andia ko kalo mau jalan kaki dari itu kota pung sablá pi sablá, na, itu makan waktu tiga hari.<bt>Knowledgable people about the Bible (=experts) say at that time Isra'el was enemies with Asiria, and that is why Yunus hated them (extreme). Perhaps/it was entirely possible (idiomatic) that he had family or people he knew who were victims. Nevermind that the people of Niniwe didn't know/recognise/acknowledge God. So (consequently) God was asking Yunus to go serve/minister to people whom he hated and viewed with prejudice/disparagingly, and Yunus excessively stored his liver (=grudge, stew). Niniwe was the big/important/capital city of the country of Asiria. There were 120,000 people who lived in the city of Niniwe. That is why if (someone) wanted to walk from one side of the city to the other, it would take/eat three days. [EXEG: TN, Allen, NET; see extended note at 1:1 about Jonah's prejudice towards Israel's enemy.]</bt></note>Pi kasi tau taráng-taráng sang orang dong di situ bilang, &lt;Tuhan Allah su lia bosong pung jahat. Andia ko Dia mau hukum sang bosong.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Go the/explain clearly to the people there saying, &lt;God has seen your-pl evil. That is why He is going to punish you-pl.&gt;&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Heb: ‘cry out/proclaim against it’ NLT, CEV, TH, TN, NET + note = judgment; Directions added in vs.2-3 so readers can grasp graphic significance of unknown geography. See NLT ‘opposite direction’ in vs.3. UNSs felt implicit-explicit of “who are enemies with Isra'el” is necessary to follow the high level dynamics of the book.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lfanay: in front of me;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qum (imperv): get up, stand up, start, get moving. Doesn't imply that he was lying down, but tells him to swing into action at once.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) raʕatam: their evil, wickedness. Can"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qraʔ (imperv): proclaim (not necessarily "yell") publicly "all da peopo"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕaltah (ʔlh fem): goes up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕal: proclaim over = denounce (Sasson)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕal: proclaim over = denounce"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕaltah (ʔlh fem): goes up, has gone up - like God said to Abraham about Sodom</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qraʔ (imperv): proclaim (not necessarily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) raʕatam: their evil, wickedness. Can be read "their plight," but that doesn't fit with the message of destruction that Jonah is to bear.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qum (imperv): get up, stand"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lfanay: in front of me; I have been informed of the evil they do. OR, Stuart) their trouble concerns me (doesn't fit Jonah's message of destruction)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01407c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ma Yunus sonde mau dengar. Dia mau lari jao dari Tuhan. Andia ko dia mau pi jao di sablá matahari turun sampe di kota Tarsis, andia di Spanyol. Ju dia turun pi kota Yope ko cari kapal yang mau balayar pi Spanyol. Dapa satu kapal bagitu, ais dia bayar ongkos, ju nae itu kapal. Deng bagitu, ju Yunus pikir dia bisa lari sambunyi dari Tuhan.<bt>But Yunus didn't want to listen/obey. He wanted to run/flee far from God2. That is why he wanted to go far to the west until the city of Tarsis, that is in Spanyol. And he went down to the city of Yope to look for a ship that was going to sail to Spanyol. Getting/encountering a ship like that, then he paid the fare, and went up/embarked on that ship. In that way Yunus though he could run/flee hiding from God2. [EXEG: CEV, TN, HCE, TEV, TH, on using ‘Spain’ (Tarshish = Cadiz coast of Spain); see fuller discussion in NET note.] [NOTE to daughter translations: TB uses Yafo here for Joppa, whereas in Acts it uses Yope. Use the same name you used in Acts 9-11.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) millifney yʔ: repeated, probably to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaqam (qwm): he arose, he took steps to ..., he up and ...</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕimmahem: along with them (the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) livroach: to escape, flee (away from God, where he didnʔt live)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yered: he went down (inside"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yafo: not part of Israel</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) skharah: its (fem) passage, fare,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) tarshiyshah (with locative -ah): to Tarshish (the Cadiz coast of Spain)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔoniyyah: ship"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) millifney: away from the presence of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yafo: Joppa, a northern coastal"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yered: he went down (from his home to the coast)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yimtsaʔ: he found, encountered (either"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yimtsaʔ: he found, encountered (either deliberately or by chance)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yered: he went down (from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yafo: Joppa, a northern coastal town in the territory of Dan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) millifney: away from the presence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔoniyyah: ship</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) tarshiyshah (with locative -ah): to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) skharah: its (fem) passage, fare, wages, hire</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yafo: not part of Israel"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yered: he went down (inside the ship)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) livroach: to escape, flee (away"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕimmahem: along with them (the crew). It doesn't imply that he shipped as a crew member; he was a paying passenger. (Some Jewish commentators think he bought the ship; most donʔt.)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaqam (qwm): he arose, he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) millifney yʔ: repeated, probably to emphasize the irony of trying to go somewhere that the Lord wasn't.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Angin ribut di laut, ais kapal amper mau tanggalám<bt>A storm at sea, then the ship is about to sink/drown</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ma waktu itu kapal ada balayar, ju TUHAN kirim datang satu angin ribut bésar di laut. Ais laut mangamok sampe itu kapal amper mau ancor.<bt>But when/while that ship was sailing/underway, the LORD sent coming a large/severe storm at sea. And the sea went amuck to the point that the ship was about to be destroyed. [DISCOURSE: TH, TN, Allen all set off 1:1-3 structurally as high-level book intro. Also Anderson, HCE.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lhishshaver (nif inf): be broken"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yʔ: initial position of "Lord" heightens the contrast between Jonah's idea and what God actually did. Francis Anderson, "A new development in a story may be marked by a circumstantial clause."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Hishvah (Hshb piʕel intensive): with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) heTil (Twl hif): cast from afar; UBS "implies a degree of violence and suddenness or unexpectedness." The same verb is used for heaving things overboard, including Jonah.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Saʕar: tempest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ruaH-gdolah: strong wind. "Big wind" is stiff, but possible to handle. "Bite-hard wind" is gale force, but a good crew can handle it. "Hard wind" is hurricane force, impossible to handle (DM). As far as I know, the Mediterranean is too far north and too landlocked to have full scale hurricanes / typhoons / cyclones, but it does have some pretty scary wind conditions.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yam: ocean. At this point"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yam: ocean. At this point the land was out of sight, a condition Hebrews were not familiar with. Probably "ocean", but check Pidgin use of "sea" to see how (or whether) they differentiate them.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ruaH-gdolah: strong wind. &quot;Big wind&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Saʕar: tempest</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) heTil (Twl hif): cast from"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Hishvah (Hshb piʕel intensive): with nifʕal infinitive, was near to, was almost; this is the only place where the verb "think, plan" is used of an inanimate object, sort of like "the boat like to break up." In the sailasʔ minds, the ship is about to fall apart.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yʔ: initial position of &quot;Lord&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lhishshaver (nif inf): be broken apart; came close to being broken up</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ana bua kapal dong sandiri su taku mati. Dong satu-satu batarea minta tolong sang dong pung songgo-songgo dong. Ais ju dong angka buang itu kapal pung muatan, ko biar kapal lebe ringan.<bt>The ship's crew/underlings themselves were terrified. Each of them called out asking for help from their gods/objects of traditional worship. Then they threw out the ship's cargo, so that the ship was more light(weight). [EXEG: Heb. ‘they threw the vessel's things’ is understood to be ‘cargo’ by most authorities (NRSV, NLT, CEV, TB, TN), but could also be the ship's gear. Acts 27 throws out cargo first, then ship's gear, but there are also ancient legal cases about liability for cargo jettisoned in storms. Authorities divided whether Heb. ‘to lighten for them’ refers to #1 the cargo/ship or #2 the danger. We take the first (NRSV, NLT, CEV, TB, TN). Some ballast/weight makes a ship more stable and better handling, but too much weight makes it ride low in the water and vulnerable in heavy seas.]</bt></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01411c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Naa, waktu ana bua kapal dong satenga mati cari jalan ko biar itu kapal jang tanggalám, na, Yunus su turun pi bawa, ju tidor sonu.<bt>Naa [+discourse shift], while the ship's crew were half dead (=busy with effort) trying to look for ways so that the ship wouldn't sink/drown, na, Yunus had gone down below, and was sleeping soundly. [EXEG: Heb. term can refer to ‘below deck, cargo hold, rear part of the boat’; it conveys that Jonah went as far from the hubbub as possible. TH discusses the possibility that Jonah may have gone down to sleep before the storm, and AM restructures 4-5 accordingly for chronology. TN feels the chronology of Heb. “and Jonah had gone down” is ambiguous. I agree. In my experience riding small wooden boats in bad storms out at sea over a 30 year span, one of the most common coping strategies by passengers is to hunker down and go to sleep in terror. So we retain the order of the Heb. which sets the stage a little better for flowing into vs.6, but see a basis for accepting either discourse structure. For uniform style and exegesis, follow the Kupang.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayeradam (rdm nif): he was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mallaHim: sailas</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) sfinah: ship. Used only here,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) uyizʕqu (qal): cried out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔel-yarktey: to the farthest part,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaTilu (Twl hif): they threw out, same verb as "threw a strong wind at them" in 4</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yarad: went down"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) hakelim: the furnishings of the boat, the ship's gear (does keli include the cargo? Sounds more like the things the ship was furnished with). Cargo first, gear second, food last in Acts 27 storm. There are ancient legal cases about liability for cargo jettisoned in storms.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayonah: &quot;Jonah&quot; clause initial in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lhaqel (qll hif): to lighten</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) meʕlehem: for them - make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) meʕlehem: for them - make it easier for them to manage</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lhaqel (qll hif): to lighten"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayonah: "Jonah" clause initial in a narrative. UBS again "Another circumstantial clause brings Jonah back on the scene once more" with a quick shift of viewpoint as in verse 4.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) hakelim: the furnishings of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yarad: went down</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaTilu (Twl hif): they threw"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔel-yarktey: to the farthest part, the back side (went down into the deepest part of the hold, or the farthest away from all the hubbub - most ships at that time didn't have holds)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) uyizʕqu (qal): cried out"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) sfinah: ship. Used only here, it may imply that the ship had a deck. Otherwise the picture would be of Jonah tucking himself away in the most remote corner he could find, away from the shouting sailas. The verb used is "go down," which may imply a hold, but is also just the standard form for entering a boat (like going to Egypt is always "go down").</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mallaHim: sailas"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayeradam (rdm nif): he was sleeping soundly, lay sound asleep, was senseless (how far had he walked to get to Joppa? Or did he collapse from exhaustion or terror?)</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ais waktu juragan dapa lia sang Yunus, dia masparak bilang, &lt;&lt;Woeh! Lu ni, karmana? Akurang ko lu ada sonu bagitu? Paling sadiki lu bangun. Minta tolong sang lu pung songgo-songgo. Jang sampe dia yang bisa kasi tunju rasa kasian sang kotong, ko biar kotong jang ancor buang!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then when the captain encountered/happened to see Yunus, he spoke angrily saying, &lt;&lt;Woeh [+rebuke]! What/how are you doing? (=explain yourself) Why are you sleeping soundly like that? [+challenge/rebuke] At the very least get up. Ask for help from your gods/objects of traditional worship. Perhaps/who knows whether he is the one who can show pity/mercy/compassion to us-inc, so that we are not completely destroyed!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) noʔved (ʔbd 1pl): we won't"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yiqrav: he approached. Doesn't imply that the captain was looking for Jonah and found him, but that he was there anyway and noticed him. He might have been going around checking the cargo</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yitʕashet (ʕsht hitp imperf): maybe"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) chovel: saila, crew</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔulai: perhaps - key word"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mah-lkha: what's with you? (why aren't you with the others, praying?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qum (imperv): in this case"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) nirdam (rdm nif partcpl): zonked, when he should be up and doing something to help, or praying</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) nirdam (rdm nif partcpl): zonked,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qum (imperv): in this case it does mean "get up!"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mah-lkha: what's with you? (why"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔulai: perhaps - key word for understanding pagan theology several places in the book</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) chovel: saila, crew"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yitʕashet (ʕsht hitp imperf): maybe he will remember us, think of us; he may turn out to take notice of us (kind of hopeless)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yiqrav: he approached. Doesn't imply"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) noʔved (ʔbd 1pl): we won't be destroyed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dong mau lempar buang Yunus dari kapal [\s2]<bt>They want to throw out Yunus from the ship [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Itu kapal pung ana bua dong ba'omong satu deng satu bilang, &lt;&lt;Kotong su calaka ni! Kalo kotong sonde dapa ini masala pung akar, na, pasti kotong su abis ni. Mari ko kotong hela lot ko cari tau, ini sapa pung sala.&gt;&gt; Andia ko dong hela lot, ju Yunus yang dapa.<bt>The ship's crew spoke among themselves saying, &lt;&lt;We are facing calamity/misfortune here! If we-inc don't find/get/encounter the root of this problem, na, surely we are finished/done for. Let's draw lots to find out who here has the wrong/offence/sin.&gt;&gt; That is why they drew lots, and Yunus got it. [EXEG: ellipted proposition/s reflecting worldview: this danger classifies as abnormal; abnormal danger results from sin; we need to find out whose sin is responsible; we need to deal with it appropriately to remove the danger to ourselves. (NOTE: this also reflects worldviews in the Timor region, although in Timor it is more likely to first assume that certain ancestors have been offended, before worrying about spirits or gods.). CEV undertranslates ‘lots’ and replaces it with ‘ask our gods to show us’. In our region lots are used for many purposes, so that strategy is unnecessary. As in other books referring to ‘lots’, we ‘draw lots’ rather than ‘cast lots’, reflecting local RL ways of doing the same function/getting the same result.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) gorlot: lot, a stone thrown"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔish ʔel-reʕeho: each one to his counterpart. The scene has shifted back to the part of the deck where the sailas had gotten together.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vnapilah (hif): cause to fall"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lkhu (hlk imperv): come on! this is what we'll do!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lkhu (hlk imperv): come on!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vnapilah (hif): cause to fall</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔish ʔel-reʕeho: each one to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) gorlot: lot, a stone thrown to determine a decision. "Casting lots" was like flipping a coin: is it this group or that group? is it the older ones or the younger ones? is it this person or that person? The high priest's Urim and Thummim were used in that way. Or it can be like drawing a name out of a hat, or drawing straws. The belief was that the gods guided the random choice. UBS "implies a situation where names were written on pieces of wood"</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01413c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ais ju dong batanya-tanya sang Yunus bilang, &lt;&lt;Karmana! Lu ada bekin sala apa sampe ini calaka jato kaná di kotong? Lu pung karjá apa, sampe lu nae ini kapal? Lu ni, dari mana? Lu pung asal dari mana? Lu pung orang dong, orang mana? Tolong kasi tau doo!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they questioned (repeatedly)/interrogated Yunus saying, &lt;&lt;How is it/what's going on! [+challenge] What kind of wrong have you done to the point that this calamity has fallen on us? What is your work, to the point that you got up/embarked on this ship? Where are you (coming) from? Where do you originate from? Who are your people/what kind? Please tell us now! [+pleading demand]&gt;&gt; [EXEG: From interacting with several societies in several countries, we read the logic of the order of the questions in the Heb. as follows: a) why this calamity and what is your work/task? = what do we need to know to deal with the immediate danger that you have brought upon us; b) from? country? people? = what are the relational (social and religious) risks to us if we do something to you. In this context, we see Heb. ‘your work, your task’  as aimed at finding out “What is the business that brings you on this trip, why are you on this ship, that has resulted in this calamity?” NRSV, HCE note, TH, Allen p.206, Ellison 372, Sasson p.107, TEV, Knox, ]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔattah: you (independent pronoun, rare)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) haggidah-naʔ (ngd hif imperv, paragogic h): announce, then</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕam: people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mlaʔakhtkha: your work, your task. Could also mean "What is the business that brings you on this trip, why are you on this ship?"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔey-mizzeh: where-from.this; from where"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) meʔayin: from whence do you come?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔartsekha: your land, your country"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔartsekha: your land, your country</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) meʔayin: from whence do you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔey-mizzeh: where-from.this; from where</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mlaʔakhtkha: your work, your task."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕam: people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) haggidah-naʔ (ngd hif imperv, paragogic"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔattah: you (independent pronoun, rare)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Yunus manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Beta ni, orang Ibrani.<bt>Yunus reponded saying, &lt;&lt;I here am an Ibrani person.</bt><note reference="1:9" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Orang Isra'el dong subu dong pung diri bilang “orang Isra'el” kalo deng dong pung orang sandiri. Ma orang laen kanál sang dong bilang “orang Ibrani”. Tagal Yunus ba'omong deng orang luar, andia ko dia kasi kanál dia pung diri pake nama yang dong su tau, andia “orang Ibrani”.<bt>The people of Isra'el referred to themselves as &lt;&lt;Isra'el people&gt;&gt; when with their own people. But other people knew them as &lt;&lt;Ibrani people&gt;&gt;. Because Yunus was speaking with outsiders, that is why he introduced himself using the name they would know, that is &lt;&lt;Ibrani person&gt;&gt;.</bt></note>Beta sémba sang TUHAN Allah di langit, yang bekin ame laut deng darat samua.<bt>I worship the LORD God in heaven, who made  both the sea and the land (inclusive). [NOTE: Jonah responds to the 2nd set of questions and ignores the 1st set.] [EXEG: ‘Hebrew’ is the outsider term the sailors would have known. ‘YHWH’ here as identifier name to distinguish from all the other gods of the sailors. (Carter. 2005. Use of ‘Yahweh’ in Pijin OT.--but we are not using it since the Catholics are banning Bibles that use Yawe (2008)) HCE, Cf. TN, discussion in TH. TN: sea &amp; land = whole world. Allen “Yahweh's universal sovereignty” “no mere local deity”. Heb. yareʔ ‘one who fears’ here is also ‘revere/worship/respect’ as in BART note for this verse.] [NOTE to daughter translations: check for natural pairings ‘sea and land (darat)’ vs. ‘sea and dry land (tana karíng). Uab Meto would use the latter (pah meto).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) hayabashah: the dry land"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔivriy: Hebrew; Hebrew people called themselves "Israelites," but everybody else called them "Hebrews," so Jonah was using the term the sailas would have used.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) hashamayim: not just the far,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yareʔ (yrʔ partcple): one who fears. Jonah is using the term pro forma, just a thing you say. But in the next verse, when the sailas hear what god Jonah is talking about, they are really scared: same verb.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yareʔ (yrʔ partcple): one who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) hashamayim: not just the far, starry heavens, but the first heaven where the birds fly and the rain falls and the storms come. It includes the air all around us that we breathe. Throughout Scripture he is the God who is right here all the time. English "heavens" makes it sound like he's a long way off.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔivriy: Hebrew; Hebrew people called"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) hayabashah: the dry land</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Deng beta ada mau lari jao dari Dia.&gt;&gt;<bt>And I was wanting to/going to run/flee far from Him.&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: restructured to better fit RL discourse. Direct speech and Reason-response. HCE. TN display.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dengar bagitu ju, itu ana bua kapal dong tamba taku lai. Ju dong tanya sang Yunus bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko lu bekin bagitu?!&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing that, then the ship's crew became even more afraid/terrified. And they asked Yunus saying, &lt;&lt;Why did you do that?!&gt;&gt; [+challenge, rebuke]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) boreaH (partcpl): one who was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yiyrʔu: The sailas, who are less blasé about a potentially dangerous god, realize that Jonah could be responsible for them dying because he doesn't really believe in his God. Like Genesis 21 and Abimelech. (Rawlings)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) millifney yʔ: from the presence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕasatah: what are you up to? what are you doing? Not "what have you done?" or "why have you put us in danger?"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yadʕu: they knew, they realized;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yadʕu: they knew, they realized; or they had come to know (it doesn't say that Jonah told them directly, but sounds as if he had mentioned it casually)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕasatah: what are you up"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) millifney yʔ: from the presence of the Lord (UBS: "his Boss" rather than "the Boss," because Jonah was the only one who claimed a relationship to Yahweh)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yiyrʔu: The sailas, who are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) boreaH (partcpl): one who was fleeing (without the implication that God was chasing him - he was just trying to get to some place where God wouldn't bother him)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Naa, itu galombang dong tamba bésar tarús. Ju itu ana bua dong tanya sang Yunus bilang, &lt;&lt;Botong musti bekin karmana sang lu, ko biar ini laut bisa tanáng, ko botong bisa salamat?&gt;&gt;<bt>Naa, [+shift] those (large) waves2 kept getting bigger. And the crew asked Yunus saying, &lt;&lt;What must/should we-exc do to you-sg, so that this sea can become calm, so that we-exc can be saved/safe?&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: as above, restructured to better fit RL discourse. Reason-response. NLT, CEV, HCE.] [EXEG: ellipted proposition/s: #1 what can we do (to appease your god), #2 calm the seas (so that we can live). TH touches on both, as does Allen. HCE makes first explicit. Timor worldview should be able to carry #1 without making it explicit. CHECK.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Soʕer: stormy"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lakh: give us guidance about</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) holekh: increasing in intensity (Noah,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yishtoq (shtq imperf): so that it will become still</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) meʕaleynu: from over us"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) meʕaleynu: from over us</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yishtoq (shtq imperf): so that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) holekh: increasing in intensity (Noah, depth). In or out of quotation?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lakh: give us guidance about"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Soʕer: stormy</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lena ombak = kici; galombang ="><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">Lena ombak = kici; galombang = bésar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ju Yunus manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini. Beta su tau kalo ini angin ribut kaná sang bosong gara-gara beta. Jadi angka buang sang beta pi dalam laut sa, ko biar laut bisa tanáng kambali kasi sang bosong.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yunus reponded saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. I know that this storm has hit/affected you-pl on account of me. So (consequently) throw me out into the sea, so that the sea can become calm again for you-pl.&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: as above, restructured to better fit RL discourse. Reason-response. TN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕəleykhem: is over you, is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) saʔuni (nsʔ): pick me up, carry me</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yishtoq: will become still (echoes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) həTiyluni (Twl hif imperv): throw me out</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) həTiyluni (Twl hif imperv): throw"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yishtoq: will become still (echoes their question word for word)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) saʔuni (nsʔ): pick me up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕəleykhem: is over you, is bearing down on you - is this the beginning of compassion? (JR)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dong angka buang sang Yunus pi dalam laut [\s2]<bt>They throw Yunus out into the sea [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Biar Yunus su usul bagitu, ma itu ana bua kapal dong coba-coba ko dayung kambali pi darat dolo. Ma sonde bisa, te itu angin ribut deng galombang tamba ganas tarús.<bt>Even though Yunus suggested like that, nevertheless the ship's crew kept trying first to paddle/row back to land. But they couldn't, cuz (elaboration) the wind/storm and the (big) waves were getting increasingly fierce. [CHECK: Q: does the /ma/... /dolo/ convey that they didn't want to throw Yunus in? A: still buying time worrying about the risk.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕəleyhem: over them; against them"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaHtru: they rowed. They give it one more try before they throw Jonah overboard, because they know that killing him can get them into trouble.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) soʕer: storm"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) hashiyv (shwb hif inf): to bring back</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) holekh (partcpl): the sea kept"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaboshah: dry land</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yakholu: they could [not]"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yakholu: they could [not]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaboshah: dry land"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) holekh (partcpl): the sea kept getting worse and worse, higher and higher - they aren't getting out of it by rowing back.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) hashiyv (shwb hif inf): to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) soʕer: storm</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaHtru: they rowed. They give"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕəleyhem: over them; against them</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2015-11-19 02:28:21Z">Q:</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ju dong sambayang minta tolong sang Yunus pung TUHAN Allah bilang, &lt;&lt;Tuhan! Tolong sang botong doo! Jang kasi tenga botong ancor buang tagal botong mau angka buang ini orang pi dalam laut. Andekata dia sonde parná bekin sala, ais botong bunu bekin mati sang dia, na, jang lempar itu sala pi botong. Te Tuhan yang ator ini samua, bukan botong. Jadi botong jang pikol itu sala.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they prayed asking for help from Yunus' LORD God saying, &lt;&lt;Lord! Help us-exc! [+imperative] Don't allow us-exc to be completely destroyed because we want/are going to throw this person out into the sea. if perchance [+hypothetical] he has never done wrong/sin, and we kill him dead, na, don't throw that wrong/blame us-exc. Cuz (elaboration) God2 is the one who has handled/set up/managed all of this, not us-exc. So (consequently) we-exc should not shoulder carry that wrong/sin.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Heb. ‘in exchange for the life’ = for killing him, HCE, NLT, CEV, TH. Re: Heb. ‘innocent blood’ see discusssion in TN, TH. Hypothetical following HCE and context.] [NOTE to daughter translations: it is quite common for local lgs to express certain categories of perkara in terms of ‘blood’ (rather than death by metonymy), so discuss with team in case the literal might actually be better here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕasiyta: you did"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yʔ: Jonah's God, not their gods</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Hafatsta: you [are / have"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔanah: Oh, please, I pray! before a wish, request, statement, or command</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) naqiʔ: exempt, free from guilt;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔal-naʔ noʔvdam (ʔbd cohortative): let us not perish</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔal-titen ʕalenu dam naqiʔ: do"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) bnefesh: in exchange for the life of (Deuteronomy 19:21, 2 Samuel 14:7). on account of? for the sake of? for taking?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) bnefesh: in exchange for the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔal-titen ʕalenu dam naqiʔ: do not hold us guilty of innocent blood</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔal-naʔ noʔvdam (ʔbd cohortative): let"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) naqiʔ: exempt, free from guilt; blood of an innocent person, legal term in Deut. Jonah wasn't innocent, but what he was guilty of was not a crime. The sailors didn't know what the punishment should be.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔanah: Oh, please, I pray!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Hafatsta: you [are / have been] pleased [to do]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yʔ: Jonah's God, not their"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕasiyta: you did</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Sambayang abis, ju itu ana bua dong angka buang sang Yunus pi dalam laut. Tarús laut tadó memang.<bt>After they finished praying, then the crew threw Yunus out into the sea. Straightaway the sea became calm2. [DISCOURSE: RL tail-head linkage.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mazaʕfo: from its raging"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yisʔu (nsʔ narr): they picked up Jonah</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayaʕmod: it stood still"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yTiluhu (Twl hif): they heaved him</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yTiluhu (Twl hif): they heaved"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayaʕmod: it stood still</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yisʔu (nsʔ narr): they picked"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mazaʕfo: from its raging</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Lia bagitu ju, itu ana bua dong taku sang TUHAN. Andia ko dong horo binatang kasi sang Tuhan, ju angka sumpa sang Dia.<bt>Seeing that, the crew were afraid of the LORD. That is why they (ritually) slaughtered an animal to the Lord, and swore an oath to Him. [EXEG: Heb. ‘sacrifice’ = animal sacrifice; TN, TH, TWOT, HCE] [CHECK: what might these vows be? See discussion in TN. Discussion in TH is unhelpful to know how to expand it. A midrash says they took their families and went to Jerusalem and were circumcised as Jews, then made the sacrifices, but that's too specific (overtranslation).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ndarim: vows. A midrash says"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yiyrʔu: they were afraid</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yidru (ndr narr): they made"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yirʔah gdolah: [with] great fear - even more than in the storm</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yizbHu-zevaH: they offered sacrifice [&quot;to&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yizbHu-zevaH: they offered sacrifice ["to" sounds English; other places weʔve used "for"]</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yirʔah gdolah: [with] great fear"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yidru (ndr narr): they made a vow</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yiyrʔu: they were afraid"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ndarim: vows. A midrash says they took their families and went to Jerusalem and were circumcised as Jews, then made the sacrifices, but that's probably too specific.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01416c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ma waktu dong buang sang Yunus pi dalam laut, ju TUHAN ator ko satu ikan bésar mati pung, datang kodo ame sang Yunus. Ju Yunus ada dalam itu ikan pung parú tiga siang, tiga malam.<bt>But [+contrary to expectation] when they threw Yunus out into the sea, the LORD arranged so that a huge (extremely large) fish came and swallowed up Yunus. And Yunus was in the belly/abdomen of that fish for three days, three nights. [NOTE: in Hebrew versification, this is 2:1. In this case the Indonesian TB lines up with the English versification, rather than the Hebrew. Often it lines up with the Hebrew when there is a difference.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) shloshah yamim ushloshah leylot: three"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) dag: fish</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mʕey: body of, belly of,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) livloaʕ (blʕ inf): to swallow (without chewing)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yhi: he was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yhi: he was</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) livloaʕ (blʕ inf): to swallow"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mʕey: body of, belly of, trunk of body of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) dag: fish"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) shloshah yamim ushloshah leylot: three days and three nights</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:40</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yunus sambayang pi Tuhan Allah<bt>Yunus prays to God</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Waktu Yunus masi ada di ikan pung parú, dia sambayang sang dia pung TUHAN Allah,<bt>While Yunus was still in the fish's belly/abdomen, he prayed to his LORD God,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) hadagah: locative? female?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yitpallel (pll hitp): pray</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔəlohayw: his God (does this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔəlohayw: his God (does this make sense in Pidgin?). UBS suggests that "his god" contrasts with the gods of the sailas; the usage here does not sound like Yahweh is the only god in the scene.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yitpallel (pll hitp): pray"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) hadagah: locative? female?</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />bilang,<bt>saying, [STYLE: structured as poetic ritual language parallelism, typical of Biblical Heb. poetry as well as poetic language in Timor region. See: Joseph E. Grimes, 'Outlines and overlays', Language 48:513-524 (1972), James J. Fox. (1988). To speak in pairs. Cambridge UP. C.&amp;B.D. Grimes, (1996) If we speak in pairs, do we translate in doublets?]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Waktu beta ada susa deng sangsara,<bt>&lt;&lt;When/while I was in difficulty and distress,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">beta batarea minta tolong sang TUHAN,<bt>I shouted/cried out asking for help from the LORD, [NOTE to daughter translations: check if lightens or makes heavy information load to go direct speech here and below in same verse.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ais Dia manyao, ko tolong sang beta.<bt>and (result) He answered/responded, to help me. [EXEG: Heb. ‘answer’ is understood here as ‘respond’ to the cry for help by helping. HCE, TN. The TH comment that this is a verbal response is silly in the context. Various authorities discuss the problem of the Hebrew tense. We take it as internal to the situation from the belly of the fish, supported by several sources.. The tense shouldn't look back as though his troubles were over already.] [DISCOURSE: Use of 3rd person for direct address is common in Timor lgs. See discussion in TN. This verse is parallelism typical of Heb poetry, and also typical of ritual language poetry structure in Timor region lgs. Direct address using 3rd person title shifting to 2s pronoun common in region.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Waktu beta ada dalam ikan pung parú,<bt>When/while I was/am in the belly/abdomen of the fish,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">itu sama ke beta ada di orang mati dong pung tampa.<bt>that is as if/like I am in the place of the dead people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ais beta pange minta tolong dari situ,<bt>Then I called asking for help from there,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ju Tuhan dengar, ko tolong sang beta.<bt>And God2 (You) heard, and/to help me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) shiwwaʕti (piʕel): call for help"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(cn) Oh, good, you make it second person (you) when talking to God!!! This is the only third person in the prayer.  Was jalike I [stay] inside [da middle a] da Mahke Peopo Place.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) shəʔol: the abode of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayoʔmer: no object, ʔhe thoughtʔ</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) beTen: belly, womb; deep inside,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qaraʔti: call out. If this is a prayer from inside a fish, the tense shouldn't look back as though his troubles were over already.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaʕəneni: he answers me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) tsarah: distress, often wit</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) tsarah: distress, often wit"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaʕəneni: he answers me</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qaraʔti: call out. If this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) beTen: belly, womb; deep inside, in the midst of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayoʔmer: no object, ʔhe thoughtʔ"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) shəʔol: the abode of the dead, usually called "Da Mahke Peopo Place"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Oh, good, you make it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) shiwwaʕti (piʕel): call for help</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Possibly an overlay structure? Or a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">Possibly an overlay structure? Or a disjunction between meter and syntax? Joseph E. Grimes, 'Outlines and overlays', Language 48:513-524 (1972), for all you consultants out there; also The Thread of Discourse, Mouton (1975). If it's an overlay, each plane should probably be set as a separate stanza.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="clause structure doesn't match scansion"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">clause structure doesn't match scansion</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Tuhan lempar buang sang beta pi tenga laut,<bt>God2  (=you) threw me out into the middle of the sea (=deep sea), [NOTE: in RLs this also evokes far from any shore.] [NOTE to daughter translations: some lgs would use ‘black sea/laut itam’ for this. Check Mat. 18:6 and Mrk. 9:42.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sama ke banjer yang sapu bawa sang beta,<bt>and it is/was like a flood which swept me away,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ju galombang yang Tuhan kirim dong,<bt>and the (big) waves that God2  (=you) sent, [EXEG: while Heb. has waves possessed, Timor lgs would have to attribute agency. Also HCE.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">hantam barmaen sang beta.<bt>kept pummeling me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕavaru: pass from one side"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) tashliykheni: you cast me down. (This is a fuller description of the "trouble" referred to in the preceding verse. It refers to the conditions before he starts praying. If itʔs an overlay, this is Plane 3 starting through the situation again. But how do overlays come through to Pidgin speakers?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) galleykha: wave, billow (whatʔs that?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mtsulah: the depths of the ocean (Not "Jalike"; the depths of the the ocean is quite literally where he was.)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mishbarekha: your breakers (at the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) bilvav yamim: in the heart of the ocean</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mtswlh and lbb ymym are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) nahar: river, probably used here in the sense of ocean currents</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yəSovəveni (sbb piʕel or poʕel):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yəSovəveni (sbb piʕel or poʕel): surround, go all around</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) nahar: river, probably used here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mtswlh and lbb ymym are glosses of each other, but both original</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) bilvav yamim: in the heart"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mishbarekha: your breakers (at the seashore). Here, probably means the breaking waves in the open ocean during a storm. But "surfs" is a shore thing. Can such things be possessed in Pidgin? See the NT field for an alternative.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mtsulah: the depths of the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) galleykha: wave, billow (whatʔs that? like a swell? or a wave in the open ocean?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) tashliykheni: you cast me down."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕavaru: pass from one side to the other, overcome. Identical with Psalm 42:7b</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lagu Puji dong 42:7</note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Ais beta pikir bilang,<bt>Then I thought saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Tuhan su usir buang sang beta,<bt>&lt;God2 has gotten rid of me/kicked me out/evicted me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ko biar sonde usa lia sang beta lai.<bt>so that (He) doesn't have to see me/look at me anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pasti beta sonde dapa lia,<bt>Surely I will not be able to see,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Tuhan pung ruma sambayang yang barisi lai.&gt;<bt>God2's (=Your) holy house of worship again.&gt; [EXEG: textual problem interpreting Heb. here. See discussion in TN, TH. We follow what the Heb. actually says, rather than what some scholars think it should say. On the negative reading, see discussion in TH, CEV, HCE, MM, and context. For ’temple’ we leave open multiple readings, as per our protocols, but ‘heaven’ makes more sense in the context of about to die, than does ‘temple in Jerusalem’. See also TN, TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qadshekha: your holy place"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) nigrashti (nif): I have been driven away. Like Psalm 31:22.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔel-hekhal: temple, palace - not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) neged: in front of</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lhabiT (nbT hif): look at"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔakh: certainly, only. Where does the negative idea come from? Or is this ʔeykh ʔhow will I ever look at your temple again?ʔ Another possibility is that Jonah is going back and forth between the prayer he actually prayed, and a commentary on it: "And yet, here I am, back at your Temple in Jerusalem!"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔosif (ysf hif): I continue"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔosif (ysf hif): I continue</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔakh: certainly, only. Where does"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lhabiT (nbT hif): look at</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) neged: in front of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔel-hekhal: temple, palace - not usual thoughts when dying</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) nigrashti (nif): I have been"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qadshekha: your holy place</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Sadiki lai beta su mati,<bt>In a little while (=soon) I will already be dead, [EXEG: NRSV and NLT undertranslate Heb. ‘waters surrounded me as far as my soul/life,’ or ‘threatening my soul/life’, but it is reflected in CEV, HCE, TB, TN.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te galombang dong hantam barmaen sang beta,<bt>cuz (elaboration) the (big) waves keep pummeling me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng aer ada tutu ame sang beta,<bt>and the water is closing over me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ju rumput laut dong feo ame beta pung kapala.<bt>and2 the seaweed [lit: ocean grass, lexicalised; they farm it here] is wrapping around my head. [NOTE: nice view from inside the stomach?]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Havush (partcpl passive): get wrapped"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔəfafuni: it closed me in</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Suf: reeds, rushes; seaweeds? (FF"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕad: unto, toward</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yəSovveni (Sbb polel): go around,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) nefesh: life, desire, awareness. Also means "throat," so it could mean "the water closed in on me and choked me so I couldn't breathe." Given that the Hebrews were consummate landlubbers, they may not have had much of a vocabulary for drowning.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) təhom: great quantity of water,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) təhom: great quantity of water, the deep ocean</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) nefesh: life, desire, awareness. Also"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yəSovveni (Sbb polel): go around, encircle. Can be threatening or helpful</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕad: unto, toward"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Suf: reeds, rushes; seaweeds? (FF 171). May refer to any plant that grows in the water; in the case of ocean far from land, probably "seaweed" rather than "reeds" as in "Sea of Reeds," the Red Sea.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔəfafuni: it closed me in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Havush (partcpl passive): get wrapped around something</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="6" />Beta turun tarús sampe di gunung pung kaki,<bt>I keep going down/descending to the feet/base of the mountain/s,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">yang ada di laut pung dasar.<bt>that are at the base/floor of the sea. [EXEG: HCE, CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Itu sama ke beta turun pi orang mati dong pung tampa,<bt>That is like I descend to the place of the dead people,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ju dong konci mati sang beta di sana.<bt>and they lock me in tight/imprison me  there (remote).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Sonde mungkin beta bisa kaluar lai!<bt>It is not likely/probable that I will be able to go out again!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ma Tuhan ni, beta pung TUHAN Allah!<bt>But God2/Lord, You-sg are my LORD God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tuhan angka ame sang beta dari calaka di bawa,<bt>God2 (=You) have lifted me up/rescued me from the calamity/misfortune below, [EXEG: Heb. pit, destruction, grave. TWOT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">deng kasi salamat sang beta, ko biar beta jang mati!<bt>and saved me, so that I don't die!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mishshaHat: from the grave, the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lqitsvey harim: to the roots of the mountains, the base. Like Haleakala, which rises from 20,000 feet below sea level to 10,000 feet above, making it the tallest mountain in the world as measured from its base. This phrase goes grammatically with the last line of Verse 5; the rest stands alone.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) taʕal (ʕlh hif): you raised"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) haʔarets briHeah: of the earth, the bars on the gates, to shut the underworld (pun on baraH ʔfleeʔ?)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) haʔarets briHeah: of the earth,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) taʕal (ʕlh hif): you raised me up</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lqitsvey harim: to the roots"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mishshaHat: from the grave, the pit (Isaiah 38:17 = Sheol)</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="7" />Waktu beta su rasa mau putus napas,<bt>When I felt I was about to breath my last (breath),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng beta pung nyawa mau ilang buang,<bt>and my soul/life force was about to disappear, [DISCOURSE: RL poetic parallelisms appropriate for contemplating death.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">beta inga sang TUHAN,<bt>I remembered the LORD,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng beta pung sambayang minta tolong,<bt>and my prayer asking for help,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">sampe di Bapa pung ruma sambayang yang barisi sana.<bt>arrived/reached Father's (=Your) holy house of workship yonder (remote).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) tfilati: my prayer"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) hitʕaTTef (ʕTp hitp inf): when I fainted; when my life was slipping away? slipping into despair</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) zakharti: I remembered"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) zakharti: I remembered</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) hitʕaTTef (ʕTp hitp inf): when"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) tfilati: my prayer</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="8" />Samua orang yang maen songgo,<bt>Every person who (dabbles in) traditional worship,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sémba sang barang yang sonde ada pung guna dong.<bt>worships2 things that have no use/value/substance.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dong bale balakang deng tola buang sang<bt>They turn their backs on (symbolic action) and reject</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tuhan yang suka kasi tunju hati bae sang dong,<bt>(the) God2 who likes to show his good liver/goodness/kindness/generosity to them,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">deng suka tolong orang yang bata'ika deng Dia.<bt>and likes to help people who are bound/linked to Him. [NOTE to daughter translations: check how you've handled Heb. /chesed/ in Gen. 24:12 (Here chasdam covering the last two lines, but same root)] [EXEG: this is a difficult expression in Hebrew (see discussion in TN and NET Notes), and English translations and commentators differ greatly, depending on how they translate chesed, which means “grace, kindness, loyalty, unfailing love,” and what they understand by the expression “their grace.” TN: The two main possibilities are:  (1) “their grace” means “the LORD’s grace to them,” that is, the love and kindness which the LORD would have shown them if they had believed in him rather than worshiping idols. See NIV, CEV, JB, NLT; Allen, p. 215; Sasson, p. 167. (2) “their grace” means “the loyalty which they should show to the LORD.” So the TEV has translated this part of the verse: “have abandoned their loyalty to you.” See also RSV, GW, NCV, NET; Stuart, p. 478; Baldwin, p. 471. There are volumes written about the many meanings of chesed, and our insights should be tied in with that. I see the core range of meaning hovering around English glosses such as “loving-kindness” and “unfailing love”. The first captures the core range, and the second touches on the well documented element ‘covenent loyalty’. NIV's attempt to force this to equate with NT Gk charis ‘grace’ is really unhelpful in this context making it close to nonsensical. While there is overlap, the core meanings are not the same, and ‘grace’ really doesn't fit this context of talking about the pagan sailors, and neither does ‘loyalty’. NET Bible makes the best sense to me here of the English translations, “Those who worship worthless idols forfeit the mercy that could be theirs.” (which interestingly isn't too far from the KJV). [NOTE: AM seems to capitalise every occurrence of TUHAN, rather than just those that reflect YHWH in the Heb, in spite of the note in the forward.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaʕzovu (qal): abandon, acts here"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mshamrim (piʕel): those who worship</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) HaSdam: the one who shows"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) havle-shawʔ: vanity of worthlessness; probably refers to idols.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) havle-shawʔ: vanity of worthlessness; probably"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) HaSdam: the one who shows loyalty toward them (a quality of God, the most likely)? the one they show loyalty to? the loyalty they show to others? the results of their being loyal (implied in Tanakh)? loyalty, solidarity, faithfulness, community relations, protection. Hesed can be translated fairly consistently as "stick wit," but here it's not clear who is sticking with whom. Translations differ.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mshamrim (piʕel): those who worship"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaʕzovu (qal): abandon, acts here like an antonym of HeSed - no longer show any loyalty. loʔ HaSdam yaʕzovu sounds like an oxymoron.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="9" />Ma beta mau bawa korban sukur ko sémba<bt>But I want to/am going to bring a *sacrifice of *thanksgiving to *worship</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">deng angka nae lagu puji sang Tuhan!<bt>and lift songs of praise to You/God2!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Apa yang beta su janji tu,<bt>That which I have promised,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sakarang beta mau bekin ame.<bt>now I am going to do them (successfully/to completion-svc).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te TUHAN Allah yang ada pung kuasa,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the LORD God is the one with the power/authority,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ko kasi salamat sang beta na!&gt;&gt;<bt>to save me! [+emphatic]&gt;&gt; [EXEG: ‘deliverance, salvation’ here in Heb. seems to be able to be read either as a general statement, or a fix of Jonah's specific trouble here. Our protocols push us to leave both options open.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yshuʕatah: help, deliverance, salvation. I've"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔezbəHah-lakh (zbH cohortative): let me sacrifice to you (a "may I" or "let me" type of wish, not a statement of intention, so "goin" is a little too strong). It contrasts with "Dey no like stick wit you" in v. 8</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔəshallemah (piʕel cohortative): let me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) bqol todah: with a voice of praise; thanksgiving offering, appreciation, song of thanksgiving Isaiah 51:3</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) nadarti: I make a vow"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) nadarti: I make a vow to you</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) bqol todah: with a voice"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔəshallemah (piʕel cohortative): let me pay you (another wish)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔezbəHah-lakh (zbH cohortative): let me"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yshuʕatah: help, deliverance, salvation. I've tried both "get me outa trouble" and "take me outa trouble" numerous times, and people always prefer "get".</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">End of S section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01415c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ais TUHAN suru itu ikan bésar ko bawa sang Yunus pi tana karíng. Ju itu ikan pi munta buang sang dia di pante.<bt>Then the LORD ordered that large fish to take Yunus to dry land (counterpart with sea). And that fish went and vomited him out on the beach. [DISCOURSE: RL discourse needs to get irrealis command, to realis fulfilment. See also CEV. NRSV has it worded like the Heb, which also gives the resulting state. Query: What is the “like that” at the end of last sentence? A: “God ordered the fish...” is irrealis. The “like that” is both anaphoric and realis, relating what actually happened to matching the command. It is quite common in the lgs in this region.] [NOTE to daughter translations: your language might like a /bagitu/ at the end of the verse.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yabashah: on the dry land"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayaqeʔ (qyʔ hif): vomit something</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayaqeʔ (qyʔ hif): vomit something"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yabashah: on the dry land</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of P section."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">End of P section.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yunus bekin iko Tuhan pung parenta<bt>Yunus does according to/obeys God2's command</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Ais itu, TUHAN Allah ba'omong deng Yunus ulang lai. Dia suru bilang,<bt>After that/then the LORD God spoke with Yunus once again. He ordered saying,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) shenit: second; otherwise the same"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) shenit: second; otherwise the same as 1:1</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />&lt;&lt;Sakarang lu kaluar dari sini ko pi negara Asiria pung kota bésar, andia Niniwe. Pi kasi tau sang dong samua pasán yang Beta su kasi tau sang lu.&gt;&gt;<bt>&lt;&lt;Now you leave here and go to the country of Asiria's big/main city, that is Niniwe. Go tell them all the messages/the entire message/instructions that I have told you here/now.&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Heb. imperative taken more as order to get moving, than the specific action of “get up”. HCE notes.] [NOTE to daughter translations: wording is the same as Jonah 1:2, so mirror it closely. TN, TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) dover (participle): I am in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qum (qwm imperv): get up, in the sense of get moving right away</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qəriʔah: call, appeal, formal proclamation;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ninweh haʕiyr haggdolah: unusual construction, same as 1:2. It doesn't imply that there is another Nineveh, not a great city. It may be emphasizing Nineveh's prominence (hence "da main town Assyria side"), or it may be previewing the last statement in the book about Nineveh.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ninweh haʕiyr haggdolah: unusual construction,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qəriʔah: call, appeal, formal proclamation; cognate accusative with qraʔ.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qum (qwm imperv): get up,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) dover (participle): I am in the process of revealing to you (not "I wen tell you befo")</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yunus 1:2</note><v n="3" />Ais Yunus bangun memang, ko pi kota Niniwe, iko TUHAN Allah pung parenta sang dia.<bt>And/so Yunus got us straight away, to go to the city of Niniwe, following/obeying/according to the LORD God's command to him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) dvar: word, matter"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaqam (qwm narr): Jonah got right on it this time, no dawdling. Doesn't mean "he got up out of bed" as it does in some contexts</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaqam (qwm narr): Jonah got"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) dvar: word, matter</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01417c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">(Naa, kota Niniwe tu, talalu bésar. Kalo orang jalan kaki dari sablá pi sablá, itu makan waktu tiga hari.)<bt>(Naa, [+shift] that city of Niniwe was very large. If/when a person foot walked from edge to edge, it ate/took three days.) [DISCOURSE: Writer's explanatory background to the reader.] [EXEG: Heb. ambig between “3 days to walk through it” or “3 days to visit it all. Most authorities go with the first, although NLT goes with second.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mahəlakh: distance, length of journey?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) haytah: was (fem), not referring to past glory</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕir-gdolah leʔəlohim: a super-large city:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕir-gdolah leʔəlohim: a super-large city: superlative? Genesis 1:2; 23:6. Sasson argues that a superlative would be with a construct. Stuart, important to God.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) haytah: was (fem), not referring"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mahəlakh: distance, length of journey? Requiring three days to visit? The walled city covered 1,800 acres. Babylon was 2,500 acres. Joshua 15:45 and 13:17 talk about associated villages. And the king prohibits grazing, which can't be done inside the walled city itself. So it's not clear if three days is a boundary to boundary measure including all the surroundings (as if it were ʕbr), or if it's the kind of town that it takes three days to visit on foot (which sounds more like hlk, the verb in the text).</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Waktu Yunus su sampe di sana, dia mulai jalan kuliling dalam kota. Dia jalan satu hari anteru. Ais ju dia mulai batarea ko kasi tau orang Niniwe dong bilang, &lt;&lt;Bosong orang Niniwe dong, dengar bae-bae! 40 hari lai, Tuhan Allah mau kasi ancor buang sang bosong deng ini kota Niniwe ni!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yunus had arrived there, he began to walk around in that city. He walked for an entire day. And then he began to shout out to tell the people of Niniwe saying, &lt;&lt;You-pl people of Niniwe, listen carefully! In 40 more days, God is going to completely destroy you and this city here!&gt;&gt; [DISCOURSE: Opening vocative is how shouted announcement/info is done in this region.] [EXEG-1: Heb. ambiguous: 1) walked for a day and then began proclaiming; 2) proclaimed as he began walking. We lean toward the first. If you can preserve the ambiguity, go for it.] [EXEG-2: Heb vb is more than just “tell”; semantics implies groups of people could hear him “proclaim”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) nehpakhet (hpk nif): be turned,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayachel laboʔ (chll hif narr): he began to go in - he probably spoke to groups of people as he went. Herodotus said that there were parts of the city of Babylon that didn't find out it had been captured by the Medo-Persians for three days, it was so big.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayiqraʔ: he cried out, proclaimed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mahəlakh: one day's journey</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mahəlakh: one day's journey"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayiqraʔ: he cried out, proclaimed the following message. "Tell" doesn't sound right with the addition of "so everybody can hear", needed because this was addressed to everyone, not just a conversation with one or two.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayachel laboʔ (chll hif narr):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) nehpakhet (hpk nif): be turned, overturned, destroyed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01420c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Dengar bagitu, ju orang kota Niniwe dong parcaya Tuhan pung pasán kasi sang dong. Ais dong putus bilang, &lt;&lt;Aduuu! Kotong su calaka ni, ma! Mari ko kotong samua puasa deng sambayang.&gt;&gt; Jadi samua orang, kici-bésar, pake karong goni ko jadi tanda bilang, dong su manyasal deng tobat dari dong pung jahat.<bt>Hearing that, the people of the city of Niniwe believed God2's message to them So they decided saying, &lt;&lt;Aduuu! [+regret, grief] We-inc are done for [lit: calamity is ours]! Let's (inc) all fast and pray.&gt;&gt; So (consequently) everyone, small-big, wore gunny sacks as a sign that they felt regret and repented from their evil. [DISCOURSE: RL tail-head linkage; and made direct speech following RL preferences.] [EXEG: “fasting” is taken as iconically evoking the complex activity of “fasting and praying” as per HCE. Although I don't think TN “fasting to show God that they had really repented” is wrong, rendering it like that in Kupang leaves too many ellipted propositions. “Fasting and praying” implies repentance and seeking rescue. Fuller explication of purpose of sack cloth here (see TH, TN, HCE, NLT, CEV) helps link to high level discourse of the whole story.] [CHECK: Adiii vs. Aduuu. Checked: personal preferences. Both work.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qtanam: their small people, young"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayaʔminu (ʔmn hif): they trusted, believed. "Trust in God" is literal; "trust in the message from God" is the idea. Gen 15:6.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) gdolam: their great people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) tsom: a fast</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) saqim: clothes of sackcloth, burlap."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yilbashu: they put on [clothes]. This started before the king got involved.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yilbashu: they put on [clothes]."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) saqim: clothes of sackcloth, burlap. "Stay sorry fo da bad kine stuff dey wen do" may be overkill since "sorry" itself is simply an implication of why people wore sackcloth.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) tsom: a fast"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) gdolam: their great people</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayaʔminu (ʔmn hif): they trusted,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qtanam: their small people, young peopo</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="CHECK Adiii"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">CHECK Adiii</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:4-5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 12:41, Lukas 11:32</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ais waktu Niniwe pung raja dengar samua yang jadi tu, ju dia turun dari dia pung korsi parenta, ais dia buka dia pung pakean raja, ko ganti pake karong goni. Ais dia pi dudu di abu ra'o ko kasi tunju dia pung rasa manyasal.<bt>After that/then when the king of Niniwe heard everything that had happened, he descended from his ruling chair (throne), and took off his king's clothes, to change them wearing gunny sack. Then he went and sat in ashes to show his feelings of regret/remorse.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔefer: dust, dirt, ashes"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayigaʕ (ngʕ hif): got as far as the king. Doesn't imply that the king actually heard Jonah say it, but that something reported to the king, and it doesn't say whether the message that reached the king was what Jonah said, or that people were repenting, or that they had proclaimed a fast.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) saq: sackcloth. The fabric is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayaʕver (ʔbr hif) ... meʕalaw: made his robe pass [over his head] away from him, took off his robe</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yaykhaS (kSh piʕel): he covered,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔaderet: mantle, cloak, robe. To the consultant: Hawaii was an internationally recognized kingdom until the U.S. took it over by a coup in the 1890s. It still has a royal palace, a crown, robes, and tombs of the kings. People are quite aware of that part of its history.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔaderet: mantle, cloak, robe. To"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yaykhaS (kSh piʕel): he covered, concealed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayaʕver (ʔbr hif) ... meʕalaw:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) saq: sackcloth. The fabric is known, but wearing it with the meaning of grief or sorrow is not, so it needs to be made explicit. Same for sitting in the ashes or dirt.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayigaʕ (ngʕ hif): got as"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔefer: dust, dirt, ashes</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="abu ra'o = dust (n); ra'u"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">abu ra'o = dust (n); ra'u = scoop (v)</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ais itu, ju raja kirim orang pi di kota Niniwe anteru ko suru dia pung rakyat datang bakumpul. Ais dia kasi tau sang dong samua bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini. Kotong pung idop jahat su bekin kotong calaka. Jadi beta, bosong pung raja ni, deng pagawe tinggi dong su putus bagini: samua orang musti puasa ko biar kotong bisa sambayang minta ampon. Jang makan, jang minum. Binatang dong ju bagitu.<bt>After that, the king sent people throughout the entire city of Niniwe to order his populace to come gather/assemble. The he told them all saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. Our-inc evil live have brought us calamity/misfortune. So (consequently) I, your king, and the high officials have decided like this: everyone must fast so that we-inc can pray asking for *forgiveness. Don't eat, don't drink. The animals must also be/do like that. [EXEG: The Heb. vb glossed by several as “had a proclamation made” is noted by TWOT that the Hiphel form connotes “assembly”, hence HCE “call the people together”. First part of quote to tie back into higher level story.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yishtu: they will not drink"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(cn) This IS what the text says; but can you imagine people making animals "fast"?? <span class="Italic">(7) </span>\cn   SS used to have a pig farm. "We learned that if you watch at midnight on Christmas, they go down on their knees, but we never saw it. But we didn't hear about making them fast." We all shrugged our shoulders and decided to invoke the translator's prerogative of translating rather than explaining. Sounds like a typical politician's overstatement that doesn't fit reality.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yirʕu: they will not graze"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayazʕeq (hif): call the people together</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mʔumah: something, anything"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) miTTaʕam hamelekh: by decree of the king</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yiTʕəmu: they will not taste"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) gdolayw: and his great ones, his officials</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) baqar: herd, cattle"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) baqar: herd, cattle</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) gdolayw: and his great ones,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yiTʕəmu: they will not taste</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) miTTaʕam hamelekh: by decree of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mʔumah: something, anything</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayazʕeq (hif): call the people"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yirʕu: they will not graze (only of animals)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) This IS what the text"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yishtu: they will not drink</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Samua orang musti pake karong goni. Binatang dong ju bagitu. Deng bagitu kotong kasi tunju kotong pung rasa manyasal. Samua orang musti batarea ko minta tolong sang Tuhan dari hati yang barisi. Samua orang musti barenti kasi tenga dong pung idop bekin jahat. Samua orang musti barenti maen tendes, barenti siksa deng bekin sangsara orang laen.<bt>Everyone must wear gunny sack. The animals must also be/do like that. In that way we will show our feelings of regret/remorse. Everyone must shout out/cry out asking for help from God2 from a clean/pure liver. Everyone must stop and abandon/leaving behind their life of doing evil. Everyone must stop pressing/oppressing, stop mistreating/tormenting/torturing and causing misery/suffering to other people. [EXEG: Heb. “mightily, urgently, earnestly” we take as the latter, following NLT, CEV, TH] [NOTE to daughter translations: talk about ways of doing violence and intimidating or hurting others. The Heb. is more than just physical violence. Look for generics, but not too broad/vague as “bekin jahat”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Hamas ʔəsher bkhapehem: the violence"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayitkaSSu (kSh hitpaʕel): they are to cover themselves, hide</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) darku: from their habitual, evil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) bHazqah: with strength, mightily</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vyashuvu: they are to turn"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vyashuvu: they are to turn back from their evil way</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) bHazqah: with strength, mightily"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) darku: from their habitual, evil ways</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayitkaSSu (kSh hitpaʕel): they are"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Hamas ʔəsher bkhapehem: the violence which is in their hands. The Assyrians intimidated everybody and ruled their empire by terror, but they also understood justice and religious devotion. Check if "stop hurting odda peopo" is a deliberate initiative, against "pau hurt odda peopo" which is more of a state in which, for whatever reason, they don't hurt anybody any more. WE CHECKED. IT IS DELIBERATE.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Kalo kotong samua bekin bagitu, jang sampe Tuhan lia deng dengar sang kotong, ais Dia pung hati yang panas bisa dingin, ko biar Dia kasi tunju Dia pung rasa kasian deng sonde kasi ancor buang sang kotong!&gt;&gt;<bt>If/when we-inc all do like that, perhaps God2 will see and hear us, and so His hot/angry liver can become cool/appeased/quelled, so that He shows His pity/mercy and does not completely destroy us!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: going for meaning, using local metaphors. Although Heb is “relent. back off, reconsider, have pity/compassion” TWOT, HCE; for local RLs avoid the idea in some English versions of “God changing his mind”. Can of worms. NRSV in 9-10 is unfortunate.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vloʔ noʔved: and we won't"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mi-yodeaʕ: who knows? This is not a conditional "if we come sorry an pau make lidat, den he goin pau stay huhu wit us ...", but a desperate gamble - there's a chance it's not too late, but we don't really know for sure, so let's give it a try. And "If we wen come sorry" doesn't mean the right thing; it conveys "we had a chance to come sorry but we didn't come sorry". 10 times in HB. 2 Sam 12:22, God might or might not respond emotionally. He didn't for David or Joel, but he did for Mordecai and Nineveh. Joel 2:12-14 relent, Ex 34. Dn 3:18 even if he does not, ... Jer 18:8 I will relent ... reconsider. Jonah is read at Yom Kippur, to remind people that if Nineveh repented, anybody can repent, even Israel. God gives people tremendous freedom to repent. Before the exile.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) meHaron ʔapo: turn from his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vniHam (nHm nif): repent, be sorry; relent, have compassion, back off</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vniHam (nHm nif): repent, be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) meHaron ʔapo: turn from his anger; usually pairs with ʔaf</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mi-yodeaʕ: who knows? This is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vloʔ noʔved: and we won't get destroyed</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01419c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Orang Niniwe dong manyasal deng tobat<bt>The people of Niniwe feel remorse and repent</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Waktu Tuhan lia kalo dong su rasa manyasal deng barenti dari idop bekin jahat bagitu, ju Dia rasa kasian, deng Dia pung hati panas jadi dingin. Ais Dia sonde kasi ancor buang sang dong.<bt>When God2 saw that2 they already felt regret/remorse and stopped from their living doing evil like that, He felt pity/mercy, and His hot liver became cool. Then/so He did not destroy tham. [EXEG: see comment at vs. 9. God is actively responding to people's choices. This is consistent with scripture here and as a whole, but be very careful how it is phrased. You don't want to have God breaking his promises.  The rabbis pointed out long ago that God knows the consequences of all possible choices a person has; so if a person changes his earlier choice, God has already provided for changing the consequences. RY: God's prophecies of judgment are conditional.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕal-haraʕah ʔsher-diber laʕsot-lahem: thinking about"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ki-shavu midarkam haraʕah: that they had turned around from their evil way</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yinnaHem (nHm nif): he was"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yinnaHem (nHm nif): he was sorry, repented. The Greek idea that God is locked in and can't change doesn't match Scripture - The rabbis pointed out long ago that God knows the consequences of all possible choices a person has; so if a person changes his earlier choice, God has already provided for changing the consequences. RY: God's prophecies of judgment are conditional.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ki-shavu midarkam haraʕah: that they"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕal-haraʕah ʔsher-diber laʕsot-lahem: thinking about the evil that he had spoken of doing to them</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yunus jengkel, tagal Tuhan kasi tunju rasa kasian<bt>Yunus is angry/upset/offended, because God2 shows pity/mercy</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Ma Yunus talalu jengkel, tagal Tuhan kasi tunju rasa kasian sang orang Niniwe dong. Ju dia makan gigi sang Tuhan bagitu.<bt>But Yunus was very upset/angry/offended, because God2 showed pity/mercy/compassion to the Niniwe people. And he ate his teeth (idiom: furious) to God2 like that. [NOTE: AM “Tuhan seng jadi hukum orang...Niniwe” is unfortunately ambiguous, potentially implying a kind of impotence or incompetence on God's part. MM “nyanda jadi” is similar.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yiHar (Hrh): his anger broke"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayeraʕ (rʕʕ): be bad, evil, sad fo somebody. Also used of Moses. Not just confused or melancholy or discouraged. He had a beef with God.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayeraʕ (rʕʕ): be bad, evil,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yiHar (Hrh): his anger broke out, he became indignant, furious (Outa Egypt 34:6; Joel 2:13; Songs 86:15; Nehemiah 9:17; Songs 145:8, 103:8, 2 Records 30:9, Songs 111:4)</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kaluar dari Masir 34:6; Yoel 2:13; Nehemia 9:17; Lagu Puji dong 86:15, 103:8, 111:4, 145:8, 2 Sajara Isra'el deng Yahuda 30:9</note><v n="2" />Ais dia sambayang ko mangomel sang TUHAN Allah bilang, &lt;&lt;Awe', Tuhan! Ini samua ni jadi parsís ke yang beta omong waktu beta masi di beta pung negrí sandiri tu. Andia ko beta mau lari jao pi Tarsis. Te beta tau bilang, Tuhan ni pung hati bae, deng suka kasi tunju rasa kasian. Tuhan sonde capát mara, ma hati ponu deng sayang kasi orang yang bata'ika deng Dia. Tuhan sadia kasi ampon sang orang yang minta ampon, deng siap ko sonde kasi hukum orang yang su bartobat dari dong pung jahat.<bt>Then/so he prayed to complain to the LORD God saying, &lt;&lt;Awe' [+critical, objection], Lord/God2! All of this has happened exactly like what I said when I was still in my own country. That is why I wanted to run/flee far away to Tarsis. Cuz (elaboration) I knew that God2 (=You) have a good liver (good character, kind, compassionate, generous), and like to show pity/mercy/ compassion2. God2 (You) are not quick to anger, but (Your) liver is full with love towards people who are mutually bound/linked to You. God2 (You) are ready/prepared to grant forgiveness to people who request forgiveness, and ready2/prepared2 to not punish people who have already repented from their evil. [HIGH level: This shows Jonah's strong prejudices/bigotry towards the Ninevites. Alhough we can't document it, as Israel's enemies, there is a strong chance that Jonah had family and friends killed by the Assyrians. (JEG). See also discussion at 4:3-4 in TN.] [EXEG: Last sentence doubled up to try to get at different aspects of elusive concept of Heb chesed “loving-kindness, unfailing love/mercy”. See discussion at Jonah 2:8.] [NOTE to daughter translations: in the last sentence, be careful to avoid the impression that God is holding back now, but will find another/better time to punish the evildoers.] [EXEG: Heb ‘relent’ in this context. Avoid the theologically problematic “change his mind”.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vnicham ʔal-haraʕah (nchm nif partcpl):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayitpallel (hitp): he prayed</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔafayim: your two nostrils (your"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔanah (intrj): I pray! Please!</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔerekh: long"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) həloʔ: isn't it the case? for something the speaker doesn't like</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) chesed: kindness, solidarity, joint liability."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕad: up to</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) rachum: compassionate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔadamti (ʔədamah): my own land</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔel-chanun: a god who is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕal-ken: so, therefore, that is why</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) livroaH: to flee"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qidamti (piʕel) + inf: anticipate doing something, do something for the first time</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qidamti (piʕel) + inf: anticipate"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) livroaH: to flee</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕal-ken: so, therefore, that is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔel-chanun: a god who is merciful, gracious, friendly. Like Ex 34:5-7. Not Greek categories; this is what Jews saw. Man is different from God.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔadamti (ʔədamah): my own land"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) rachum: compassionate</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕad: up to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) chesed: kindness, solidarity, joint liability. This is not "love an aloha"; it's loyalty and consistency - a key term throughout the Old Testament and into the New (stick wit yoa peopo)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) həloʔ: isn't it the case?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔerekh: long</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔanah (intrj): I pray! Please!"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔafayim: your two nostrils (your anger)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayitpallel (hitp): he prayed"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vnicham ʔal-haraʕah (nchm nif partcpl): you repent, are sorry</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kaluar dari Masir 34:5-7</note><v n="3" />Tuhan. Biar bunu bekin mati sang beta sakarang sa. Te ada lebe bae beta mati, ko sonde usa idop lai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Lord/God2. Go ahead and just kill me dead. Cuz (elaboration) it is better that I die, for there is no need to live anymore.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Jonah's anger is making him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕattah: now</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Jonah's problem is coexisting with"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qaH-naʔ ʔet-nafshi: take my life from me</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qaH-naʔ ʔet-nafshi: take my life"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(cn) Jonah's problem is coexisting with Assyrians, even if they've repented. Their track record was terrifying. Even a prophet had trouble with them. Only God can love the world.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕattah: now"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(cn) Jonah's anger is making him depressed, but depression isn't his problem. Anger is.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="End of S section"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">End of S section</Message></Annotation><note reference="4:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">1 Raja-raja dong 19:4</note></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01424c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ma TUHAN manyao sang Yunus bilang, &lt;&lt;Sonde pantas kalo lu mara bagitu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But the LORD reponded to Yunus saying, &lt;&lt;It's not right/appropriate that you are angry in that way!&gt;&gt; [EXEG: RQ]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Harah: he is angry, hot"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) heyTev (yTb hif inf): to do good, do well; is it good? "o wat?" makes it a yes-or-no question with an edge to it. There's a still pushier form, but it doesn't sound right here.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) heyTev (yTb hif inf): to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Harah: he is angry, hot</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yunus tunggu ko mau lia Tuhan mau bekin karmana sang orang Niniwe dong<bt>Yunus waits to see what God is going to do to the Niniwe people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Jadi waktu Yunus su kasi tau abis Tuhan pung pasán kasi sang orang Niniwe dong, ju dia kaluar dari itu kota. Dia pi di kota pung sablá matahari nae, ais kasi bangun satu laak ko bisa dapa sombar. Dia dudu di situ ko mau lia Tuhan bekin karmana sang orang Niniwe dong.<bt>So (consequently) when Yunus had finished telling/explaining God2's message to the people of Niniwe, then he went out from the city. He went to the eastern side of the city, and then built a (temporary) shelter (poles, thatch roof, no walls) so he could get shade. He sat there wanting to see what/how God2 was going to do with the people of Niniwe. [DISCOURSE: First clause RL tail-head linkage for higher level cohesion.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) batsel: in the shadow"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qedem: east</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) sukah: branches across some supports"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) sukah: branches across some supports for shade. This is the area north of where the Desert Storm battles were, and to the north of Baghdad, pretty hot and dry except for the big Tigris river that flows by Nineveh.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qedem: east"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) batsel: in the shadow</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Stuart suggests 5-11 is a flashback"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">Stuart suggests 5-11 is a flashback to the time before Nineveh repents, but it is moved to end because it shows the point of the book. Yom Kippur: Jonah shows God's mercy</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01422c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ju TUHAN Allah kasi tumbu satu pohon malata ko biar dia pung daon kasi sombar di atas Yunus pung kapala. Deng bagitu, Yunus sonde kaná panas talalu, ais dia sanáng lia itu pohon.<bt>And/then the LORD God caused to grow a vine/climbing plant so that its leaves would give shade above Yunus' head. In that way, Yunus was not overly effected by heat, so he was happy/pleased to see that plant. [EXEG: Heb. qiqayon: ricinus vine, castor bean <span class="Italic">Ricinus communis,</span> a vine which grows quickly to nine or ten feet tall. (See TH, NRSV note, HCE note, TB) Indonesian /jarak/: the plant from which they get /minyak jarak/ or /kastroli/ ‘castor oil’ from. See if your language has a specific term for this plant, and if it is known by the average villager (city people are less likely to know it). Otherwise generic ‘vine’ is probably better than substituting ‘gourd’, ‘cucumber’ or ‘pumpkin’, the latter of which usually grows on the ground in the Timor region. In Kupang they think castor oil is from the /damar/ plant, which is not a vine.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayishmaH ... shimHah: he rejoiced"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayman (mnh): appoint, destine (same word as for the fish)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) meraʕato: from his misfortune (not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qiqayon: ricinus vine, castor bean <span class="Italic">Ricinus communis,</span> which grows quickly to nine or ten feet tall. Some translations say "gourd", others "cucumber" or "pumpkin," but that sounds like from before England got into castor beans. SS knows plants, including castor beans, very precisely; he's raised them as a crop. JO also knows the castor bean, but her family considered them a nuisance plant in their yard, because they weren't that much into farming. SK isn't familiar with plants of that kind. With the differing attitudes, maybe it's better not to go into botanical details, and just say "a plant."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lhatsil (ntsl hif): deliver"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lihyot: for there to be</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) tsel: shadow, shade"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) tsel: shadow, shade</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) lihyot: for there to be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) lhatsil (ntsl hif): deliver</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qiqayon: ricinus vine, castor bean"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) meraʕato: from his misfortune (not specifically "hot") - relief from rʕh v. 1</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayman (mnh): appoint, destine (same"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayishmaH ... shimHah: he rejoiced a lot</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="one tall castor bean plant ..."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">one tall castor bean plant ...</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ma dia pung beso amper siang, ju Tuhan kirim ulat datang makan buang itu pohon, ais dia mamalek buang.<bt>But early the next morning, God2 sent worm/grub to eat up that plant, so it shrivelled up. [NOTE: CEV incorrectly capitalizes ‘Lord’ in 7-9. Heb. does not use YHWH here.] [EXEG: TH notes Heb ‘a worm’ can be taken in either the singular, or the collective sense (a [type of] worm). We leave it unmarked for number to it can be taken either way and for naturalness.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayivash (ybsh qal): shrivel. Not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) tolaʕat: generic for any insect larva or worm. In the 1950s the army worm attacked the castor bean plants growing in up country Maui, and also the pineapples. The Maui cowboys (they had cowboys there before the western U.S. had them) had castor bean growing as cattle feed, because it grows in dry locations. The cattle chew the leaves. Somebody also planted castor bean to use in aircraft oil, but it wasn't profitable enough to stay in business. [Castrol uses it as an additive in oil for race car engines and sells a lot to wannabe racers.] The army worm chews the bark, making smaller plants wither; a big plant isn't necessarily killed when the bark is chewed. The pineapple farmers (the translator was one at the time) used Parathion followed by Malathion to kill the worms, and sprayed diesel oil on the roads to keep the worms from entering other fields. "Attack" was the word people used then for the worm infestation (SS), but SK prefers the more generic "go afta."</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vatakh (nkh hif): hit, attacked"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) shaHar: the reddish light before the dawn. Not "dark"</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) maHərat: next day"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) maHərat: next day</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) shaHar: the reddish light before"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vatakh (nkh hif): hit, attacked</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) tolaʕat: generic for any insect"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayivash (ybsh qal): shrivel. Not just dry up, but become misshapen - hence "any kine." "Poho" fits better; it means incapable of functioning as was intended, in this case incapable of giving shade or producing beans.</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Ju waktu hari su panas, Tuhan kirim datang satu angin panas yang fuu dari sablá matahari nae. Itu panas kaná di Yunus pung kapala, sampe dia rasa tabakar ko mau samaput. Dia rasa mau mati sa. Ais dia masparak sang Tuhan bilang, &lt;&lt;Akurang ko Tuhan sonde kasi biar beta mati?! Ada lebe bae beta mati sa. Sonde usa idop bagini lai!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then when the day became hot, God2 sent a hot wind which blew from the east. The heat hit/touched/affected Yunus' head, to the point that he felt (sun)burned about to faint/collapse. He felt like he just wanted to die. So he spoke angrily to God2 saying &lt;&lt;Why don't God2 (you) just let me die?! It would be better if I just died. There is no need/reaon to live like this anymore.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayishʔal: demanded"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) kizroach (inf): when the sun rose</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vayitʕalaf (hitp): he became faint,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) qadim: east wind, scirocco, doesn't cool you down</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) takh (nkh): hit, attack"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Harishit: sharp, hot (of a wind)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Harishit: sharp, hot (of a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) takh (nkh): hit, attack</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) qadim: east wind, scirocco, doesn't"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayitʕalaf (hitp): he became faint, started to feel woozy, lose his senses (feel all covered up, surrounded, like things wrapping around him)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) kizroach (inf): when the sun"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vayishʔal: demanded</Message></Annotation></p>
    <fig path="cook\cot\co01423c.tif" rtfFormat="width:4.0cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ju Tuhan balas sang Yunus bilang, &lt;&lt;Lu pikir lu bisa mara tagal itu pohon malata su mati, ko? Lu pung hak apa? Lu ni, sapa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then God2 responded to Yunus saying, &lt;&lt;You think that you can be angry because that vine has died, ko? [+tag] What right do ou have? Who are you?&gt;&gt; (Last is kind of like "Who the hell do you think you are?" [EXEG: Heb. RQ, purpose = scold, TN, HCE note. ‘about the plant” = because the plant had died; see TH, TN, HCE, NLT.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yunus manyao bilang, &lt;&lt;Deng beta bagini mara ni, biar beta mati sa! Te itu yang pantas.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yunus responded saying, &lt;&lt;With my being angry like this, just let me die! Cuz (elaboration) that is what is fitting/appropriate.&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Harah-lkha: anger breaks out for"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) yoʔmer: he said. He's not asking for information; he's pushing Jonah, so "aks" is too specific.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) haheyTev (yTb hif): makes it"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) haheyTev (yTb hif): makes it good</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) yoʔmer: he said. He's not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Harah-lkha: anger breaks out for you</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Tuhan mau kasi tunju Dia pung rasa kasian [\s2]<bt>God2 wants to show His pity/mercy [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ma TUHAN Allah kasi tau sang Yunus bilang, &lt;&lt;Bagini. Itu pohon muncul datang satu malam. Dia pung beso, itu pohon mamalek buang. Capát sa! Padahal lu sonde karjá apa-apa ko bekin itu pohon jadi idop. Lu sonde karjá sadiki ju ko bekin itu pohon batumbu. Biar bagitu, ma lu rasa kasian ko sonde mau itu pohon ancor buang.<bt>But the LORD God told/explained to Yunus saying, &lt;&lt;It's like this. That plant appeared one night. The next day that plant was shrivelled up. (It happened) so quickly! Whereas in fact you-sg did not work/do anything to make tha plant become alive. You did not work/do even a little to make that plant grow. Even that being the case, nevertheless you felt pity/mercy/compassion and didn't want that plant to be destroyed.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔavad: become lost, perish, be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) Hasta (Hws): you were troubled about, you looked compassionately on it</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) shebin: which between"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʕamalta: do work, toil</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) vloʔ gidalto (piʕel): raise a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) vloʔ gidalto (piʕel): raise a plant, made it get big</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʕamalta: do work, toil"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) shebin: which between</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) Hasta (Hws): you were troubled"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔavad: become lost, perish, be ruined, fail</Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Jadi sakarang pikir bae-bae so'al Beta ni. Kira-kira bae ko sonde, kalo Beta rasa kasian deng sonde mau ko itu orang Niniwe dong kaná ancor buang? Te di situ ada lebe dari 120.000 orang, tamba lai deng dong pung binatang samua. Apalai itu orang Niniwe dong sonde tau mana yang bae, deng mana yang jahat, sama ke orang yang sonde tau mana yang tangan kanan, deng mana yang tangan kiri. Andia tu!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) now think carefully about Me here. Is it perhaps good or not, if I feel pity/mercy/compassion and don't want the people of Niniwe to be destroyed? [NOTE: lexical tie with end of vs.10] Cuz (elaboration) there are more than 120,000 people, not including/adding further all their animals. Furthermore those people of Niniwe don't know which (of choices) if good, and which is evil, like a peron doesn't know which is the right hand and which is the left hand. That's the way it is! [+discourse emphatic]&gt;&gt; [EXEG: Heb. “12 units of 10,000”. Jerusalem maxed out at 24,000.] [DISCOURSE 10-11: God's speech bracketed by “Bagini .... Andia tu!” is to help convey that God is making a point here. There is a connection between the image plant and the people of Niniveh. Strengthened by lexical cohesion between “you feel pity for the plant, not wanting it to be destroyed” and “I feel pity for the people of Niniveh, not wanting them to be destroyed.” See discussion in TH, TN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) Needs to sound like God"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(cn) good! You put the meaning first.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔadam: people (collective; single person"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(cn) We've tried both ways, and also tried not giving the meaning. This pattern is the one the translators always choose when the options are presented.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) mishteym-ʕesreh ribo: more than 12"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔaHuS (HwS): look compassionately on</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) harbeh (rbh hif inf abs):"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) harbeh (rbh hif inf abs): cause to become many</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(ne) ʔaHuS (HwS): look compassionately on"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) mishteym-ʕesreh ribo: more than 12 myriads (units of 10,000). Jerusalem at its maximum was 24,000, so Nineveh was five times as big.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) We've tried both ways, and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(ne) ʔadam: people (collective; single person is a late meaning). Some think it's children, but that doesn't track with ʔadam. households?</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="(cn) good! You put the meaning"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2014-12-15 11:14:56Z">(cn) Needs to sound like God is making a point (an den!), not just that he's commenting that there sure are a lot of people and animals in there. Most English translations fizzle on this one. Midrash Yonah says that at that point Jonah fell on his face and acknowledged God's mercy. Jonah is making the point for the Jews.</Message></Annotation></p>
  </book>
</bible>